WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Going diving for the first time was an incredible experience.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
All of a sudden, colors are very different, sound seems to come from all directions.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
On a coral reef, life is everywhere.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
It's just everywhere.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And from that point forward, I knew that I really wanted to specialize on these deeper reef communities.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.000
In 2016, we actually saw a major event that affected coral reefs around the world.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
It's estimated that we lost about half of the coral on the Northern Great Barrier Reef.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Actually witnessing that bleaching firsthand was a major turning point in my career.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:58.000
From that point onward, I started to feel a real responsibility to start studying these reefs in a way that could more actively contribute to their survival.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:08.000
So my group at the California Academy of Sciences uses imaging and genomic methods to study the ecology of coral reefs.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Things have changed for us as coral reef biologists a lot in the past couple of decades.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
With genomics and imaging technologies, it's no longer a field science.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Now, it's very much a data science.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:32.000
The data that we collect from the field, we need programming languages like R and Python to analyze our results.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
With these kind of analysis, we can actually identify the genotypes within a population that hold most promise for survival.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
At the same time, we can also see whether there's enough of those individuals to really be viable into the future.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Coral reefs are incredibly important. There's no doubt about that.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
They host 25% of marine species.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
They provide food and livelihoods to 500 billion people.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
They contribute billions to our global economy.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.000
There's no doubt that coral reefs are important.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:11.000
With these new technologies, I do have hope that we can preserve coral reefs for future generations.

